.TH "TEMPORAL.PLAINTIME.SUBTRACT" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.PlainTime.subtract \- Temporal.PlainTime.prototype.subtract()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]subtract()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R] instances returns a new
\f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R] object representing this time moved
backward by a given duration (in a form convertible by
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R]), wrapping around the clock if
necessary.
.PP
If you want to subtract two times and get a duration, use
\f[CR]since()\f[R] or \f[CR]until()\f[R] instead.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
subtract(duration)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]duration\f[R]
A string, an object, or a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instance
representing a duration to subtract from this time.
It is converted to a \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object using the same
algorithm as \f[CR]Temporal.Duration.from()\f[R].
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.PlainTime\f[R] object representing the time
specified by the original \f[CR]PlainTime\f[R], minus the duration.
.PP
Subtracting a duration is equivalent to adding its negation, so all the
same considerations apply.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Subtracting a duration
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] start = Temporal.PlainTime.from(\(dq12:34:56\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] end = start.subtract({ hours: 1, minutes: 30 });
console.log(end.toString()); \f[I]// 11:04:56\f[R]
.EE
.PP
For more examples, see \f[CR]add()\f[R].
